==============================================================================
B. LAB BENCH COMPOSITE-GEOMETRY RULES (CRITICAL — NEW)
==============================================================================

B.1 WHEN TO APPLY
Stage 1 may attach an OPTIONAL field `structure_hint` to a lab bench's entry
in `object_hierarchy`. The allowed values are:
   - "double_deck"           : worktop + upper reagent shelf
   - "oversized_island"      : single-deck island bench, length > 2.4 m
   - "double_deck_oversized" : both at once

The Stage 1 data may also be missing this field even when the image clearly
shows a double-deck or oversized bench. Apply these rules whenever EITHER
the structure_hint is present OR the object's name explicitly includes
"double-deck", "double deck", "reagent shelf", "central divider rack",
"oversized island", or similar. When in doubt and the bench depth is ≥ 1.4 m
(i.e., a double-sided island), prefer the double-deck composite.

B.2 DOUBLE-DECK BENCH COMPOSITE (4 boxes minimum, 5 boxes preferred)

⚠️  HARD RULE — INLINE EMISSION ONLY
Do NOT define any helper function that wraps `create_box` (e.g.
`def create_double_deck_bench(...)`). The downstream parser only
recognises top-level `create_box(...)` calls whose first argument is a
LITERAL string. f-strings, `+` concatenation, and unbound parameters
inside helper bodies will be silently dropped, which makes the entire
bench invisible to Stage 5/6/7/10/11/12.

Emit each part as a SEPARATE top-level `create_box(...)` call directly
inside `run_layout_engine()`. Names MUST be literal strings such as
`"IslandBench_worktop"`, `"IslandBench_post_L"`, etc.

⚠️  REFERENCE FRAME (READ CAREFULLY — common bug source)
- ALL z values below are WORLD coordinates with z = 0 being the FLOOR.
- `cx, cy` are world (x, y) coordinates of the bench's vertical centerline,
  taken at FLOOR level.
- When you call `create_box(name, location, dim, ...)`, Blender places the
  CENTER of the box at `location` and stretches it to `dim` in each axis.
  Therefore a worktop with TOP at z = H_work has CENTER at z = H_work / 2,
  NOT at z = 0. Putting the worktop center at z = 0 sinks it half into the
  floor — that is a BUG.

A double-deck bench is ONE physical piece made of:
  Part 1 (worktop body, merged)  : full footprint cabinet+worktop slab
  Part 2 (left shelf post)        : vertical post rising from worktop top
  Part 3 (right shelf post)       : vertical post rising from worktop top
  Part 4 (upper shelf board)      : horizontal board ≈ 0.3 m deep, centered
                                    along the bench's long axis
  Part 5 (OPTIONAL back panel)    : vertical panel between the two posts
                                    behind the upper shelf; only for
                                    double-sided islands when the image
                                    clearly shows a centerline divider

Geometry constants (use the literal numbers below in your `create_box`
calls; do NOT factor them into a helper):
   H_work   = 0.9      worktop top height           → worktop center z = 0.45
   H_shelf  = 1.4      upper shelf TOP height       → shelf center z   = 1.38
   T_shelf  = 0.04     shelf board thickness
   D_shelf  = 0.30     shelf board depth (along bench short axis)
   W_post   = 0.05     post cross-section side
   H_post   = 0.5      post height (= H_shelf - H_work)
                                                    → post center z    = 1.15

REQUIRED INLINE TEMPLATE (copy/paste this block, then rename `IslandBench`
to the bench's actual name from Stage 1/2 such as `EastBench`, `PrepBench`,
etc.; substitute concrete numbers for `bench_cx`, `bench_cy`, `bench_L`,
`bench_D`, `bench_yaw`; rotation MUST be the same `(0, 0, bench_yaw)`
tuple for all 5 parts).

```python
import mathutils

# --- Bench transform (set these per bench from Stage 1/2 data) -------
bench_cx, bench_cy = -0.5, 0.0     # floor-level XY center
bench_L, bench_D   = 3.6, 1.5      # length × depth (long × short axis)
bench_yaw          = 0.0           # radians, Z-rotation, same for all parts
bench_rot          = (0.0, 0.0, bench_yaw)
rot_mat            = mathutils.Euler(bench_rot, 'XYZ').to_matrix()

# --- Part 1: worktop body (cabinet + slab merged) --------------------
create_box("IslandBench_worktop",
           (bench_cx, bench_cy, 0.45),                # H_work / 2
           (bench_L, bench_D, 0.9),
           bench_rot, mat_bench_top, coll_01)

# --- Part 2: left post (local x = -L/2 + W_post/2, local y = 0) ------
post_off_L = rot_mat @ mathutils.Vector(
    (-(bench_L / 2.0 - 0.05 / 2.0), 0.0, 0.0))
create_box("IslandBench_post_L",
           (bench_cx + post_off_L.x,
            bench_cy + post_off_L.y,
            1.15),                                    # H_work + H_post/2
           (0.05, 0.05, 0.5),
           bench_rot, mat_bench_frame, coll_01,
           show_direction=False)

# --- Part 3: right post (local x = +L/2 - W_post/2, local y = 0) -----
post_off_R = rot_mat @ mathutils.Vector(
    ( (bench_L / 2.0 - 0.05 / 2.0), 0.0, 0.0))
create_box("IslandBench_post_R",
           (bench_cx + post_off_R.x,
            bench_cy + post_off_R.y,
            1.15),
           (0.05, 0.05, 0.5),
           bench_rot, mat_bench_frame, coll_01,
           show_direction=False)

# --- Part 4: upper reagent shelf (depth = D_shelf, NOT bench depth) --
create_box("IslandBench_upper_shelf",
           (bench_cx, bench_cy, 1.38),                # H_shelf - T_shelf/2
           (bench_L, 0.30, 0.04),
           bench_rot, mat_bench_top, coll_01,
           show_direction=False)

# --- OPTIONAL Part 5: centerline back panel --------------------------
# Only emit when the image clearly shows a vertical divider between the
# two operator sides on a double-sided island.
create_box("IslandBench_back_panel",
           (bench_cx, bench_cy, 1.15),                # (H_work + H_shelf) / 2
           (bench_L, 0.02, 0.5),
           bench_rot, mat_bench_frame, coll_01,
           show_direction=False)
```

⚠️  Z-VALUE LOOKUP TABLE (must hold EXACTLY for every double-deck bench)

| Part            | center z | half-height | top z | bottom z |
|-----------------|----------|-------------|-------|----------|
| worktop         | 0.45     | 0.45        | 0.90  | 0.00     |
| post_L / post_R | 1.15     | 0.25        | 1.40  | 0.90     |
| upper_shelf     | 1.38     | 0.02        | 1.40  | 1.36     |
| back_panel*     | 1.15     | 0.25        | 1.40  | 0.90     |

⚠️  NAMING RULE
- Replace `"IslandBench"` with the bench's actual name from Stage 1 / Stage 2
  (e.g. `"EastBench"`, `"PrepBench"`, `"NorthBench"`).
- Each bench's 4–5 parts MUST share that prefix and have the suffixes
  `_worktop`, `_post_L`, `_post_R`, `_upper_shelf`, optionally `_back_panel`.
- DO NOT use f-strings or `+` concatenation; every name is a literal
  string.
- If the scene has multiple double-deck benches, repeat the entire 5-call
  block (with fresh transform variables) for each one. Use distinct
  prefixes (e.g. `"IslandBench"` vs `"EastBench"`) so their parts never
  collide.

⚠️  ROTATION RULE
- Every part of the SAME bench shares the SAME `(0, 0, bench_yaw)` tuple.
- The post offsets are computed in bench-local frame and rotated into
  world via
  `mathutils.Euler(bench_rot, 'XYZ').to_matrix() @ mathutils.Vector((dx, dy, 0))`
  BEFORE adding to `(bench_cx, bench_cy)`. Posts and shelves stay
  anchored to the rotated worktop.
- For axis-aligned benches (`bench_yaw == 0`) the post offsets simplify to
  pure ±X offsets from `bench_cx`; you may write the post locations
  inline as `(bench_cx ± (bench_L/2 - 0.025), bench_cy, 1.15)` instead of
  using `rot_mat @ Vector(...)`.

⚠️  COMMON BUG TO AVOID
Do NOT pass `(bench_cx, bench_cy, 0)` as the worktop's `location`
argument expecting Blender to "lift" it. `create_box` puts the CENTER
of the box at `location`, so a worktop center at z = 0 sinks half the
slab into the floor and leaves the posts and shelf floating in mid-air.
The worktop center MUST be at z = 0.45.

B.3 OVERSIZED ISLAND BENCH
When `structure_hint == "oversized_island"` (no upper shelf):
- Allow L in [3.6, 4.8] m. Pick L from the image scale; do not clamp to 2.4 m.
- D = 1.5 m (double-sided island).
- Generate ONE box  (L, D, 0.9)  for the bench worktop+cabinet body.
- Place 2–4 lab stools / chairs along EACH long side, spaced 0.8–1.2 m apart.

B.4 DOUBLE-DECK + OVERSIZED COMBO
Apply B.2 with L in [3.6, 4.8] m and D = 1.5 m. Add at least 4 chairs (two
per side). Upper shelf board length = full L (it is what makes the bench
look two-tier even when oversized).

B.5 ROTATION / ORIENTATION RULES
- For a wall-side bench: long axis runs ALONG the wall; bench depth points
  away from the wall. Operator chair sits on the away-from-wall side.
- For an island bench: long axis is the longer in-plan dimension; chairs sit
  on BOTH long sides facing the bench.
- Apply rotation around Z so that the long axis matches the orientation
  visible in the reference image. The upper shelf board rotates with the
  bench (it shares the same parent rotation).
- All parts of one bench MUST share the same world Z baseline (floor) and
  the same world rotation. Do NOT rotate the upper shelf independently of
  the worktop.

B.6 POST-WRITE CHECKLIST FOR EVERY DOUBLE-DECK BENCH

Vertical anchoring (HARD numerical assertions — verify each one before
returning the script; if any one fails, the bench will be visibly broken):
[ ] worktop_center_z  ==  H_work / 2.0          (= 0.45 m)
[ ] worktop_top_z     ==  H_work                (= 0.9  m)  ← TOP at 0.9
[ ] post_bottom_z     ==  H_work                (= 0.9  m)  ← sits ON worktop top
[ ] post_top_z        ==  H_shelf               (= 1.4  m)  ← reaches shelf top
[ ] post_center_z     ==  H_work + H_post / 2.0 (= 1.15 m)
[ ] post_height_z     ==  H_post                (= 0.5  m)
[ ] shelf_top_z       ==  H_shelf               (= 1.4  m)
[ ] shelf_bottom_z    ==  H_shelf - T_shelf     (= 1.36 m)  ← rests on posts
[ ] shelf_center_z    ==  H_shelf - T_shelf / 2 (= 1.38 m)

Horizontal & material:
[ ] Upper shelf board length matches worktop length (same L).
[ ] Upper shelf board depth = D_shelf = 0.30 m, centered on bench long-axis
    centerline (local-y offset = 0 in bench frame).
[ ] No part of the upper shelf overhangs the worktop edges.
[ ] Posts sit at the SHORT ends of the bench (local-x = ±(L/2 − W_post/2),
    local-y = 0).
[ ] Same material on worktop top + shelf board (mat_bench_top).
[ ] Posts use mat_bench_frame (off-white / metal), not mat_bench_top.
[ ] All 4–5 parts share the SAME `rotation` tuple (rotated as a rigid body).

If Stage 1/2 reports the bench position as a 3-tuple like `(x, y, 0)`,
treat it as `bench_cx = x, bench_cy = y` and IGNORE the third component;
the worktop center z is fixed at 0.45 by the inline template above.
Surface objects sitting on the bench worktop must use world
z = H_work + obj_height/2 = 0.9 + h/2 (NOT 0.45 + h/2).

==============================================================================
C. LAB CIRCULATION CONSTRAINTS (must be respected when placing benches)
==============================================================================
- Aisle between two parallel island benches:                       ≥ 1.5 m
- Aisle between a bench (or fume hood) and a wall:                 ≥ 1.0 m
- Clearance in front of fume hood / biosafety cabinet face:        ≥ 1.5 m
- Clearance in front of any chair pulled out from a bench:         ≥ 0.8 m

If the room dimensions from Stage 1 are tight, distribute the spacing
proportionally; never overlap furniture. If you find that meeting these
constraints requires a room larger than what Stage 1 reported, prefer to
slightly shrink bench length over violating circulation rules.

==============================================================================
D. LAB-SPECIFIC FURNITURE PLACEMENT HINTS
==============================================================================
- Fume hoods almost always sit AGAINST a wall, with their front face into
  the room aisle. Operators stand in front; do NOT place a chair touching
  the hood.
- Chemical storage cabinets line the perimeter walls between benches.
- Optical tables sit ISOLATED with ≥ 1.0 m of clearance on all four sides
  (vibration-sensitive; nothing should mechanically couple to them).
- Safety showers/eyewash stations sit near doorways or aisles, not behind
  benches.
- Reagent bottles, glassware, hot plates, balances → place ON the worktop
  (placement_type=="surface"); do not float them in space.
